SIMPLE: tremble
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tremble
<hw>Trem"ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Trembled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Trembling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>trembler</ets>, fr. L. <ets>tremulus</ets> trembling, tremulous,
fr. <ets>tremere</ets> to shake, tremble; akin to Gr. <?/, Lith.
<ets>trimti</ets>. Cf. <er>Tremulous</er>, <er>Tremor</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To shake involuntarily, as with fear, cold, or
weakness; to quake; to quiver; to shiver; to shudder; -- said of a
person or an animal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>tremble</qex> still with fear.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Frighted Turnus <qex>trembled</qex> as he spoke.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To totter; to shake; -- said of a thing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Mount of Sinai, whose gray top⟦br⟧
Shall <qex>tremble</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To quaver or shake, as sound; to be tremulous; as
the voice <xex>trembles</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tremble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tremble
<hw>Trem"ble</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An involuntary shaking or
quivering.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am all of a <qex>tremble</qex> when I think of it.</q>
<rj><qau>W. Black.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trembler</ent>⟦br⟧
